---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Seafarer Mortgage Help: Specialist Advice | Mortgage One"
  description="Seafarer mortgage help from a specialist broker. The common hurdles, foreign currency, the Seafarers Earnings Deduction and residency, and how to clear them."
  eyebrow="Seafarer mortgage questions"
  heading="Seafarer mortgage help: getting the right advice"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'Seafarer mortgage help', href: slug },
  ]}
  scenario="seafarer"
>
  <p>
    Yes, seafarers can and do get UK mortgages. Whether you can comes down to how your income is evidenced and finding a lender that fits how you are paid. The hurdles are well known: foreign currency pay, the Seafarers Earnings Deduction, long spells at sea and residency. None of them is a barrier with a lender that understands seafarers, and that is what specialist help gets you.
   For the full picture, start with our guide to getting a <a href="/mortgage-as-a-seafarer">mortgage as a seafarer</a>.
  </p>

  <Reassurance
    lead="Whatever your situation at sea, it is workable."
    intro="Seafarer income rarely fits a standard payslip template. That is presentation, not a problem. We regularly place clients who are:"
    lines={reassuranceLines}
    closing="If your circumstances are not listed, they are almost certainly still workable. The 60-second check is the quickest way to find out."
  />

  <h2>Whole-of-market access for seafarers</h2>
  <p>
    Most high street lenders have no policy for seafarers. We search across multiple lenders in the market who do,
    lenders experienced in contract pay, sea service documents and foreign currency income. You get access to products
    and rates that are not visible if you approach lenders directly.
  </p>
  <p>Tell us about your contract and we will confirm which lenders are open to your case.</p>

  <h2>What makes a seafarer mortgage different?</h2>
  <p>
    On paper a seafarer is a strong borrower with steady, contracted income. The trouble is that an automated high
    street check is built around PAYE payslips and a settled UK footprint, so foreign currency, a nil tax bill and time
    at sea can each trip it. Specialist help means taking your case to a lender that reads those features as normal,
    because for this line of work they are.
  </p>

  <h2>Foreign currency pay</h2>
  <p>
    If you are paid in US dollars or euros, a lender converts the income to sterling and applies a reduction to allow for
    the rate moving, then works from that figure. The size of the reduction varies, so the lender you choose matters more
    than the rate. We cover this in full on our
    <a href="/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income">foreign currency income</a> page.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Not sure which hurdle is holding you up? Tell us how you are paid and we will tell you where you stand."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>The Seafarers Earnings Deduction</h2>
  <p>
    The Seafarers Earnings Deduction (SED) is a relief from HM Revenue and Customs that removes UK income tax on
    qualifying earnings for work carried out outside the UK, claimed over an eligible period of at least 365 days
    according to HM Revenue and Customs. It is legitimate and well established, but it makes your taxable income look low,
    which an automated check can misread. The right lender works from your gross contractual pay instead. There is more
    on our <a href="/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage">Seafarers Earnings Deduction</a> page.
  </p>

  <h2>Time at sea, rotation and merchant navy pay</h2>
  <p>
    Rotational contracts and long stretches away are routine, and a lender that knows the sector treats a settled
    rotation as stable employment rather than a gap. Merchant navy crews often combine all of these at once, which we
    cover on our <a href="/merchant-navy-mortgage">merchant navy mortgages</a> page.
  </p>

  <PullQuote quote="Seafarer mortgage help is rarely about whether you qualify. It is about taking your case to the lender that reads your income fairly." />

  <h2>How does Mortgage One help?</h2>
  <p>
    Mortgage One has access to plans from the whole of market and arranges seafarer cases as a core part of the business,
    not an exception to it. We give professional advice on which lender fits how you are paid, gather the evidence an
    underwriter needs, and put your case in front of the right desk. You must be on UK soil to receive advice, so we
    confirm your circumstances properly before recommending anything.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Ready for an answer rather than another decline? Let an adviser place your case."
    label="Check Your Options"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>The evidence that packages a seafarer mortgage</h2>
  <p>
    Most of the help in a seafarer case is in the packaging, getting the right documents in front of the right
    underwriter so your income reads correctly the first time. A lender that understands seafarers will usually ask for
    an employment contract showing your rotation pattern, three to six months of payslips or remittance advices, and
    matching UK or offshore bank statements that show the credits arriving. Alongside those, a sea-service letter
    confirms your time away, while proof of a UK address and evidence of your deposit complete the file. None of this is
    unusual paperwork for a seafarer. The difference a broker makes is presenting it as a single, coherent picture rather
    than a set of documents an automated check has to puzzle over.
  </p>
  <p>
    Where the documents do not line up neatly, a short written note does a lot of work. If your pay has moved between
    currencies or employers, or your rotation means gaps between contracts, a plain explanation alongside the statements
    lets an underwriter see the pattern rather than guess at it. That is the part a specialist broker handles before the
    application goes anywhere, because the same income presented two different ways can produce two very different
    answers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The order the documents arrive in matters less than the fact that they agree with one another. An underwriter is
    reassured when the contract, the payslips and the bank statements tell the same story to the pound, and unsettled
    when they do not. Reconciling them in advance, and flagging anything that looks odd before it is asked about, is the
    quiet work that turns a seafarer case from a query into a clean decision.
  </p>

  <h2>What the right lender does with the assessed income</h2>
  <p>
    Once the income is read correctly, the arithmetic looks like any other mortgage. Many lenders work to income
    multiples of around 4.5 times the assessed figure, and some will stretch to 5 times for higher earners or certain
    professionals, always subject to their affordability and stress testing. The lever that moves your borrowing most is
    therefore the assessed income itself, which is exactly the figure good packaging protects. A discount applied in
    error, or net pay read instead of gross, can quietly shrink that number before any multiple is even reached.
  </p>
  <p>
    Deposit follows the same logic. A UK-resident seafarer paid in sterling can often access standard high-street loan to
    value levels, so the deposit looks ordinary. Where income arrives in a foreign currency or you are not UK resident,
    lenders commonly ask for more, frequently 15% to 25% or more, and some cases are best placed with expat or
    international lenders. Knowing which of those buckets your case falls into before you apply is most of the help, and
    it is the difference between a clean first decision and a decline you then have to unpick.
  </p>

  <h2>A worked example: misread, then placed</h2>
  <p>
    Take a yacht-crew captain paid 80,000 euros a year, which converts to roughly £68,000. On a first approach to a high
    street system, the income was run through an automated check that applied a 25% discount to the non-sterling pay,
    cutting the assessed figure to about £51,000 before the case had really been looked at. On that number the borrowing
    fell short of what the captain needed, and the application stalled.
  </p>
  <p>
    Re-presented through a specialist that accepts euros with a smaller discount, the same income was assessed nearer
    £61,500. The file went in with the employment contract, several months of remittance advices, matching bank
    statements showing the credits, and a sea-service letter confirming the time at sea. Nothing about the captain's
    earnings had changed. The currency, the contract and the bank credits were identical. Only the lender and the way the
    case was packaged were different, and that was enough to support the borrowing the first lender could not.
  </p>
  <p>
    Figures are illustrative. Your actual borrowing depends on your full circumstances, the lender and an affordability
    assessment.
  </p>

